         b'mmunications</a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<div id="overview">\n\n<di'
         b'v id="news">\n<h2>Announcements</h2>\n\n  <p>\n  All class-related a'
         b'nnouncements and discussion are available on the\n  <a href="http'
         b's://piazza.com/ucl.ac.uk/fall2016/computersciencem030gz03/home">M030'
         b'/GZ03 Piazza site</a>.\n  </p>\n</div>\n\n<br>\n\n<h2>Class Essent'
         b'ials</h2>\n\n<div id="essentials">\n<ul>\n<li>Instructor: <a href="h'
         b'ttp://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/B.Karp/">Brad Karp</a></li>\n<li>Tea'
         b'ching Assistant: Nikola Gvozdiev</li>\n<li>Meeting times and plac'
         b'es:<br>\nMon 11 AM - 12:30 PM, Roberts 422<br>\nWed 9:30 - 11 AM, '
         b'Drayton House B03<br>\n(occasional) Fri 5 - 6:30 PM, 25 Gordon St'
         b'reet, Math 500<br>\n<em>Lectures meet most Mondays and Wednesdays'
         b' (but not all), and on a few\nFridays. A few lectures may run a f'
         b'ull two hours, and thus end at 1 PM\n(on Mondays) or start at 9 A'
         b'M (on Wednesdays). Check the\n<a href="calendar.html">calendar</a'
         b'> for the day-by-day schedule.</em></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<img clas'
         b's="rfloat" align="right" src="paxos-isles.png">\n\n<p>\nThis class '
         b'divides roughly in half. The first half of the class\nexplores th'
         b'e design and implementation of distributed systems in\ncase-study'
         b' fashion: students read classic and recent research papers\ndescr'
         b'ibing ambitious distributed systems. In lecture, students\ncritic'
         b'ally discuss the principles that cause these systems to\nfunction'
         b' correctly, the extent to which these systems solve the\nproblem '
         b'articulated by the authors, and the extent to which the\nproblem '
         b'and solution chosen by the authors are relevant in practice.\nTop'
         b'ics discussed include consistency, fault tolerance, performance,'
         b'\ncorrectness definitions for concurrent and distributed\nexecutio'
         b'n, distributed agreement, and disconnection.\n</p>\n\n<p>\nThe secon'
         b'd half of the class explores computer system security, again\nlar'
         b'gely in case-study fashion, through the reading of research pape'
         b'rs\nand their critical discussion in lecture. Topics covered incl'
         b'ude\nsecurity properties and threat models, an introduction to\ncr'
         b'yptographic primitives and their correct use in practice, the\nKe'
         b'rberos and SSL systems, formal reasoning with certificate chains'
         b',\nsoftware vulnerabilities and exploits, exploit defenses, and s'
         b'afe\nexecution of untrusted code.\n</p>\n\n<p>\nCorrectness under'
         b' concurrency is a central challenge in distributed\nsystems, and '
         b'one that can only be fully understood through experience\nbuildin'
         b'g such systems (and encountering subtle bugs in them). To\ngive s'
         b'tudents experience of this sort, M030/GZ03\nincludes one signific'
         b'ant programming coursework in C, in which students\nimplement a s'
         b'imple distributed system that must provide an ordering\nguarantee'
         b'. Further written coursework helps students solidify their\nunder'
         b'standing of the security material in the class.\n</p>\n\n<p>\nDistri'
         b'buted Systems and Security is open to 4th-year undergraduates\n(M'
         b'030) and graduate students (GZ03). For undergraduates, prior\ncom'
         b'pletion of Networked Systems (3035) or equivalent prior experien'
         b'ce\nis a prerequisite.  For graduate students, concurrent enrollm'
         b'ent in\nNetworked Systems (GZ01) or prior equivalent experience i'
         b's required.\nDespite the differing module codes, M030 and GZ03 ar'
         b'e identical: they\nshare the same syllabus, lectures, readings, c'
         b'ourseworks, exam, and\nweighting of marks.\n</p>\n</div>\n\n</bod'
